


     LLLLOOOOOOOOKKKK((((UUUU1111))))             LLLLSSSS----DDDDOOOOSSSS 6666 ---- UUUUttttiiiilllliiiittttiiiieeeessss 1111              LLLLOOOOOOOOKKKK((((UUUU1111))))



     NNNNaaaammmmeeee
          LOOK - Determines the format of alien-format diskettes and
          displays the position of files on LS-DOS, LDOS or TRSDOS 6
          disks.

     SSSSyyyynnnnttttaaaaxxxx
          llllooooooookkkk [ ----aaaammmmppppqqqqttttuuuu!!!!????hhhh ] [[::::]_d_r_i_v_e] [ ----ffff _f_i_l_e_n_a_m_e::::_d_r_i_v_e ]
          [ ----cccc _c_y_l_i_n_d_e_r [ ----gggg _g_r_a_n_u_l_e | ----ssss _s_e_c_t_o_r ]]
          [ >>>>[>>>>] _f_i_l_e | _d_e_v_i_c_e ] [ ; _n_e_x_t _c_o_m_m_a_n_d ]

     DDDDeeeessssccccrrrriiiippppttttiiiioooonnnn
          _L_o_o_k analyzes a diskette and determines how it is formatted.
          Diskettes formatted by numerous other computers can be
          identified.  _L_o_o_k is also able to tell the difference
          between an unformatted diskette and a formatted one, even if
          _l_o_o_k doesn't know what format the diskette is in.

          _L_o_o_k will also recognize selected system formats that are
          recorded in the high-density formats that are commonly used
          today.  These include MS/PC-DOS HD, Tandy 16/6000 XENIX, and
          Tandy Model II/12/16 TRSDOS II.  (Although _l_o_o_k can
          recognize these formats, the data on these diskettes cannot
          be read by a Model III/4 system due to limitations in the
          hardware.)

          If the disk being examined is recorded in LS-DOS, LDOS or
          TRSDOS 6 format, _l_o_o_k can display the locations of the files
          on the disk.  This information can be used to help recover
          data on corrupted disks, disks with read errors, or to
          examine fragmentation of files.

          Depending on the parameters, _l_o_o_k will display information
          on all files located on a disk, or information on one
          specific file.  You can also specify a location on the disk
          and _l_o_o_k will tell you what file resides there.

          When a full display is used, each line shows the files that
          are stored in a given cylinder.  If a cylinder has more than
          four granules, the information is displayed on two lines.

          _L_o_o_k accepts several options.  Options are specified by
          single characters, and they may be entered in upper or
          lowercase.  Options are always preceded by a hyphen (a "-").
          If you are specifying multiple options, you can specify the
          options in any of these formats:
                -a -b -c   or   -abc   or   -a -bc   or  -ab -c

          The options are:

          ----aaaa   The summary of the media type and its organization will
               not be displayed.  This option is the opposite of ----tttt
               and only works on LS-DOS, LDOS and TRSDOS 6 disks.



