     LLLLOOOOOOOOKKKK((((UUUU1111))))             LLLLSSSS----DDDDOOOOSSSS 6666 ---- UUUUttttiiiilllliiiittttiiiieeeessss 1111              LLLLOOOOOOOOKKKK((((UUUU1111))))



          ----gggg _g_r_a_n_u_l_e
               Used with the ----cccc option.  ----gggg is used to specify the
               _g_r_a_n_u_l_e to analyze.   ----gggg cannot be used with ----ssss or ----ffff.

          ----ssss _s_e_c_t_o_r
               Used with the ----cccc option.  ----ssss is used to specify the
               _s_e_c_t_o_r to analyze.   ----ssss cannot be used with ----gggg or ----ffff.

          >>>>[>>>>] _f_i_l_e | _d_e_v_i_c_e
               By specifying a file or device, the output is sent to
               the specified file or device instead of the display.
               This is known as _r_e_d_i_r_e_c_t_e_d _o_u_t_p_u_t.  For example, the
               command llllooooooookkkk ::::1111 >>>> ttttyyyyppppeeee::::0000 stores the output of _l_o_o_k in
               the file TTTTYYYYPPPPEEEE::::0000.  If >>>>>>>> is used, _l_o_o_k will append the
               output of _l_o_o_k to the existing contents of the
               specified file or device.  _F_i_l_e_s_p_e_c_s for redirection
               may not specify a password.

          ; _n_e_x_t _c_o_m_m_a_n_d
               After _l_o_o_k completes, the remainder of the command line
               is executed as a second command.  The command llllooooooookkkk
               ::::5555;;;;ttttiiiimmmmeeee will report on the disk in drive 5, and then
               the time will be displayed.

          <SHIFT>@
               When pressed during output to the display, the output
               will pause.  Pressing any other key resumes output.
               Pressing this key is ignored when output is redirected.


     FFFFiiiilllleeeessss
          _L_o_o_k reads the DDDDEEEEFFFFAAAAUUUULLLLTTTTSSSS////MMMMAAAADDDD file and uses any default
          options that are specified there.  For example, if you
          wanted _l_o_o_k to omit the headers by default, the following
          entry in the DDDDEEEEFFFFAAAAUUUULLLLTTTTSSSS////MMMMAAAADDDD file would do this:
                      LOOK -Q
          Options in the DDDDEEEEFFFFAAAAUUUULLLLTTTTSSSS////MMMMAAAADDDD file are ignored if the ----!!!!
          option is specified on the command line.

          It is important that the DDDDEEEEFFFFAAAAUUUULLLLTTTTSSSS////MMMMAAAADDDD file be present on a
          logical drive with a number lllloooowwwweeeerrrr than the floppy drives you
          may use to test alien diskettes.  _L_o_o_k will search for the
          DDDDEEEEFFFFAAAAUUUULLLLTTTTSSSS////MMMMAAAADDDD file until it is found or all disk drives have
          been checked.  Some alien diskettes formats can confuse LS-
          DOS/TRSDOS 6 and may hang the operating system if this
          search tries to examine an alien diskette.  (MS-DOS
          diskettes will do this.)  By placing DDDDEEEEFFFFAAAAUUUULLLLTTTTSSSS////MMMMAAAADDDD on a drive
          with a logical number lower than the test floppy drive you
          use, you can prevent LS-DOS/TRSDOS 6 from accidentally
          trying to read an alien diskette.  The best performance can
          be obtained by placing the DDDDEEEEFFFFAAAAUUUULLLLTTTTSSSS////MMMMAAAADDDD file on drive 0.




