     LLLLOOOOOOOOKKKK((((UUUU1111))))             LLLLSSSS----DDDDOOOOSSSS 6666 ---- UUUUttttiiiilllliiiittttiiiieeeessss 1111              LLLLOOOOOOOOKKKK((((UUUU1111))))



          The ooooffffffffsssseeeetttt field specifies where in the sector to start
          comparing for the pattern that is to be tested.  In most
          cases, this value will be zero.

          The ccccoooouuuunnnntttt field indicates how many bytes are specified in
          the ppppaaaatttttttteeeerrrrnnnn field.  Note that this is the count of bytes
          specified, and this includes any escape characters.  The
          ccccoooouuuunnnntttt and ppppaaaatttttttteeeerrrrnnnn fields are separated by one or more
          spaces.

          The ppppaaaatttttttteeeerrrrnnnn consists of one or more bytes (as specified by
          ccccoooouuuunnnntttt) that are compared against the data read from the
          diskette.  If the pattern completely matches the data on the
          diskette, the format has been found.

          _L_o_o_k recognizes two escape sequences in the ppppaaaatttttttteeeerrrrnnnn field.
          The sequence 0xff 0x00 will match any character in this
          position on the diskette being tested.  This is used to skip
          a byte that changes on diskettes of the same format.  A good
          example of the use of the "wildcard" sequence would be on a
          LDOS, LS-DOS or TRSDOS 6 diskette, as these systems place
          the number of the directory cylinder in the boot sector.
          The remaining bytes at the start of the boot sector never
          change in these operating systems, so by telling _l_o_o_k to
          skip the one byte, a single entry in the LLLLOOOOOOOOKKKK////IIIINNNNIIII file can
          be used to identify all of these formats.

          The other escape sequence is 0xff 0xff, which is treated as
          a single occurrence of 0xff.  If an 0xff appears in the
          sector on the diskette you want to test, you must use 0xff
          0xff in the pattern to match it.

          Finally, the ssssttttrrrriiiinnnngggg field contains the description that _l_o_o_k
          will display when a match is found in the LLLLOOOOOOOOKKKK////IIIINNNNIIII file.
          The string must be enclosed in double-quotes and will be
          displayed exactly as it appears.  The description must be
          completely on one line.  Disk formats that have a directory
          structure identical to LDOS, LS-DOS or TRSDOS 6 should place
          a plus ("+") as the first character of the ssssttttrrrriiiinnnngggg field.
          This informs _l_o_o_k that the file allocation maps can be
          computed and displayed for this disk.  (Using this character
          on incompatible formats will have unpredictable results.)













     Page 5                                             May 15th, 1993






     LLLLOOOOOOOOKKKK((((UUUU1111))))             LLLLSSSS----DDDDOOOOSSSS 6666 ---- UUUUttttiiiilllliiiittttiiiieeeessss 1111              LLLLOOOOOOOOKKKK((((UUUU1111))))



          Entries in the LLLLOOOOOOOOKKKK////IIIINNNNIIII can be broken across one or more
          lines by using the back-slash character ("\") at the end of
          the line being split.  You must split the line between
          entries, and you cannot split the ssssttttrrrriiiinnnngggg field across two or
          more lines.  For example:
                2,0,1,0,12 0xeb,0x3c,0x90,0x49,0x42,0x4d,0x20,0x20 \
                            0x35,0x2e,0x30,0x00 \
                            "MS-DOS 5.0"
          Note that the comma between fields is implied when a line is
          split, and must not be included.  Extra spaces between
          fields are ignored.

          In most cases, any new entries should follow the entries for
          that sssseeeeccccttttoooorrrr ssssiiiizzzzeeee and ccccyyyylllliiiinnnnddddeeeerrrr/sssseeeeccccttttoooorrrr numbers that are
          already in the file.

          Finally, you can place comments in the LLLLOOOOOOOOKKKK////IIIINNNNIIII file.  Lines
          that start with a #### are ignored.  Try to keep comments to a
          minimum, as the presence of large numbers of comments will
          affect the speed of _l_o_o_k.


          If you need more information on _l_o_o_k(U1) or if you want to
